    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1863-11-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1863-11-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="573" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d573">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Dayton.</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 428.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1863-11-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">November</hi> 10, 1863.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Your despatch of October 21 (No. 366) has
                            been received.</p>
                <p>The subject of a license for the exportation of the French tobacco
                            through our blockade has been heretofore much discussed here with a
                            disposition to do an act of liberality towards the imperial government.
                            But recently that disposition has been much embarrassed by the
                            proceedings at Brest in regard to the Florida, and the discovery of the
                            armament of pirates at Nantes and Bordeaux, for hostilities <pb facs="0648" n="1326" xml:id="pg_1326"/> against the United States.
                            The subject will again be considered by the President, in view of the
                            very prompt and honorable proceedings of the imperial government in
                            arresting the armaments in the French ports, and Mr. Mercier will be
                            informed of the decision.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William</hi> L. <hi rend="smallcaps">Dayton</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c.,
                                &amp;c.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
